<span id="freeTextContainer14003178086932576301">Willhelm is a pitiful character. Overthinker. Daddy-Issues-Meter cranked to the maximum possible level. Wife left him, but won&apos;t divorce him. Still expects alimony. He can&apos;t marry his girlfriend on account of him still being married to his wife. Failed at college. Failed at pursuing his acting career. Oh so gullible. Used by everyone around him. Swindled out of money. I could relate to him on a very fundamental level, despite having nothing in common.<br/><br/>Why does life suck so much? Is there any hope</span>
  <span id="freeText14003178086932576301" style="display:none">Willhelm is a pitiful character. Overthinker. Daddy-Issues-Meter cranked to the maximum possible level. Wife left him, but won't divorce him. Still expects alimony. He can't marry his girlfriend on account of him still being married to his wife. Failed at college. Failed at pursuing his acting career. Oh so gullible. Used by everyone around him. Swindled out of money. I could relate to him on a very fundamental level, despite having nothing in common.<br /><br />Why does life suck so much? Is there any hope for change? Is there even any point in wondering all of this? Maybe "The Here and Now" is all that matters... not the past, not the future but just Right Now. Just maybe...<br /><br /><blockquote>"From his mother he had gotten sensitive feelings, a soft heart, a brooding nature, a tendency to get confused under pressure."</blockquote><br /><br /><blockquote>"Maybe the making of mistakes expressed the very purpose of his life and the essence of his being here. Maybe he was supposed to make them and suffer from them on this earth."</blockquote><br /><br /><blockquote>"So many people nowadays were [cynical]. Noone seemed satisfied, and Willhelm was especially horrified by the cynicism of successful people. Cynicism was bread and meat to everyone. And irony too. Maybe it couldn't be helped. It was probably even necessary. Willhelm, however, feared it intensely. Whenever at the end of the day, he was unusually fatigued, he attributed it to cynicism."</blockquote></span>
