<div id="review_489224602" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/489224602" />
    <a title="Alan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5650849-alan"><img alt="Alan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1310234599p2/5650849.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/489224602?book_show_action=true">Dec 29, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alan" href="/user/show/5650849-alan">Alan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5650849-alan?shelf=american-lit">american-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer489224602" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13951627834859864459"> In my five-book intro to lit class taught at a community college, I often included this novella or Alice in Wonderland or Tom Sawyer or Slocum&apos;s Sailing Alone. You can see I was not adhering to either chronological or authorial order or pigeonholing.<br/> Bellow&apos;s short work evokes the America that Reagan and Bush advertise, the Market, the go-getters... New York in a word. (And, aware of current candidates from both US parties, I should add, the Losers.) Yet being Bellow, he raises essential questi</span>
  <span id="freeText13951627834859864459" style="display:none"> In my five-book intro to lit class taught at a community college, I often included this novella or Alice in Wonderland or Tom Sawyer or Slocum's Sailing Alone. You can see I was not adhering to either chronological or authorial order or pigeonholing.<br /> Bellow's short work evokes the America that Reagan and Bush advertise, the Market, the go-getters... New York in a word. (And, aware of current candidates from both US parties, I should add, the Losers.) Yet being Bellow, he raises essential questions, and he frames an America which derives from the Old World and hastens toward a Newer One.<br /> Among Bellow's best works, this is chiseled and funny, with an aura of in-betweeness, defeat, separation, joblessness-- to the point of a changed name. <br /> Tommy Wilhelm's sister paints. "She worked very hard, but there were fifty thousand people in NY with paints and brushes, each practically a law unto himself. It was the Tower of Babel in paint"(32).<br /> "Was Tamkin a lunatic, then? That sick Mr Perls at breakfast had said there was no easy way to tell the sane from the mad, and he was right about that in any big city and especially in NY…Every other man spoke in a language entirely his own, which he had figured out by private thinking.."(83).<br /> Tommy Wilhelm to Tamkin, "You can spend the entire second half of your life recovering from the mistakes of the first half."(86) Tamkin, "Talking always about spontaneous emotion and open, receptive and free impulses, he was about as expressive as a pincushion"(96).<br /> Tamkin sees himself as dealing only in facts. "The past is no good to us. The future….anxiety. Seize the Day." (66) [The next page is very funny, for my reader to find and enjoy.]<br /> Old men control everything. "Without needs. They don't need, therefore they have. I need, therefore I don't have" (102).<br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="13951627834859864459" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

